1.1 Measurement range (Plausible values)

The measurement range of HOBO is for temperature from -20°C to 70°C in air and for light intensity from 0 to 320000 lux.

data <- data %>% 
    mutate(qcp1 = case_when(temp < -20 ~ 1, # flagging values < -20°C
          temp > 70 ~ 1, # flagging values > 70°C
          # lux < 0 ~ 1,
          # lux > 320000 ~ 1,
          TRUE ~ 0))
data

Answer: There are 0 unplausible values.

1.2 Plausible rate of change

Is there a difference of more than 1 K between two consecutive temperature values?

data <- data %>% mutate(qcp2 = if_else(abs(temp - lag(temp)) > 1 , 1, 0)) # Difference of temperature value and the previous temperature value

data %>% group_by(qcp2) %>% # groub by flag and no flag
    summarise(n = n()) %>%  # count values with and without flag

Question: Describe shortly how many data points failed during this QCP and discuss whether there is a certain daytime pattern of failure or not?

Answer: As the shortened four-week-dataset is used for the analysis, a comparison of the first temperature value with its previous value was not possible. Within the remaining dataset 7 values have been found, which had a difference to their previous value fo more than 1 K. Those values are distributed over the second and third week of the measurement and between 6 AM and 6 PM. Influences from the use of the balcony, where the HOBO was located, are possibly recognisable here.

1.3 Minimum variability (Persistence)

data <- data %>% mutate(qcp3 = if_else(temp == lag(temp, n = 1) &
                        temp == lag(temp, n = 2) &
                        temp == lag(temp, n = 3) &
                        temp == lag(temp, n = 4) &
                        temp == lag(temp, n = 5),
                       1, 0))

data_unpersistant <- data %>% filter(qcp3 == 1) %>% 
    mutate(hour = format(dttm, format="%H"))

dis_hour <- data_unpersistant %>% 
    group_by(hour) %>% # groub by hour
    summarise(n = n()) %>%  # count values 
    ungroup()
ggplot(dis_hour, aes(hour, n))+
    geom_col()

Task: Code in this section should analyses the persistance. If temperature has not changed during the last 60 minutes (i.e. data point Ti plus 5 data points before from Ti−1 to Ti−5) the corresponding data point Ti failed in this QCP.

1.4 Light intensity

data <- data %>% 
    mutate(sic = case_when(lux < 20000 ~ "cat1",
                       between(lux, 20000, 50000) ~ "cat2",
                       lux > 50000 ~ "cat3",
                       TRUE ~ "other")) %>%  # classify by Sky Illuminance Classes
    mutate(qcp4 = case_when(
                (hour(dttm) < 6 & hour(dttm) >= 18) ~ 0, #set all qcp4 values for nighttime to 1
                           lag(sic, n = 3) == "cat3" ~ 1, #set 1 if cat3 +- 3 before or ahead
                           lag(sic, n = 2) == "cat3" ~ 1,
                           lag(sic) == "cat3" ~ 1,
                           sic == "cat2" ~ 1,
                           lead(sic) == "cat3" ~ 1,
                           lead(sic, n = 2) == "cat3" ~ 1,
                           lead(sic, n = 3) == "cat3" ~ 1,
                           
                           lag(sic) == "cat2" ~ 1, #set 0 if sunshine +- 1 before or ahead
                           sic == "cat2" ~ 1,
                           lead(sic) == "cat2" ~ 1,
                           
                           TRUE ~ 0))

data

Task: Discuss shortly how often and when during daytime the QCP4 flags bad data. Elaborate on some reasons for your results.

Answer: The HOBO was attached to an interior balcony on the north side of the building. Therefore, it is plausible that no values were measured during direct sunlight.

2. Synthesis

synth <- data.frame(qcp = c("qcp1", "qcp2", "qcp3", "qcp4"),
            flags = c(sum(data$qcp1, na.rm = TRUE),
                  sum(data$qcp2, na.rm = TRUE),
                  sum(data$qcp3, na.rm = TRUE),
                  sum(data$qcp4, na.rm = TRUE)))
ggplot(synth, aes(qcp, flags))+
    geom_col()

Task: Present a table or graph to show how many data points fail during the four specific QCPs. Discuss shortly the reasons for failure and compare the different QCPs against each other.

Answer: As shown in the graph above, the most fails were detected during quality check 3. There were found 76 temperature values, which were same as their 5 previous values. In quality check 2 only 7 temperature values were detected, which differ more than 1 K from their previous value. No bad values were found in quality check 1 and 4. Fails in quality check 2 (strong change in temperature) might happended because of human influence by using the balkony. Fails in quality ckeck 3 are eventually caused by the slow reaction of temperature caused by the location of the HOBO at a inverted balcony where hardly any influence from wind etc. happens.

##    qcp flags
## 1 qcp1     0
## 2 qcp2     7
## 3 qcp3    76
## 4 qcp4     0

3. Results

3.1 Result (Flagging system: 10-minutes-values)

qc_df <- data.frame(id = data$id, dttm = data$dttm, temp = data$temp, lux = data$lux, qcp1 = data$qcp1, qcp2 = data$qcp2, qcp3 = data$qcp3, qcp4 = data$qcp4)

qc_df <- qc_df %>%
mutate(qc_tot = qcp1 + qcp2 + qcp3) %>%
mutate(flag_num = if_else(qc_tot > 0, 1, 0)) %>%
mutate(flag_txt = if_else(qc_tot > 1, "bad", "good"))

3.2 Result (Aggregate to hourly series)

hobo_hourly_dummy <- qc_df %>%
    mutate(hour = format(dttm, format="%Y-%m-%d %H")) #%>% 
hobo_hourly_dummy <- hobo_hourly_dummy %>%
    mutate(hour = cut(dttm, breaks = "hour")) %>%
    group_by(hour) %>%
    summarise_at(vars(temp, flag_num), ~ mean(.,na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
    mutate(temp_2 = if_else(flag_num < 0.3, temp, NULL)) 

hobo_hourly <- data.frame(dttm = hobo_hourly_dummy$hour, temp = round(hobo_hourly_dummy$temp_2, 4))
